{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":42248,"name":"","username":"glebedev","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/glebedev/{size}/345_2.png","created_at":"2021-04-01T08:24:34.733Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eI would like to implement something like this in Urho3D:\u003c/p\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"onebox lazyYT lazyYT-container\" data-youtube-id=\"KLjTU0yKS00\" data-youtube-title=\"IK Rig: Procedural Pose Animation\" data-parameters=\"feature=oembed\u0026amp;wmode=opaque\"\u003e\n  \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KLjTU0yKS00\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"\u003e\n    \u003cimg class=\"ytp-thumbnail-image\" src=\"https://i.ytimg.com/vi/KLjTU0yKS00/maxresdefault.jpg\" title=\"IK Rig: Procedural Pose Animation\" width=\"480\" height=\"360\"\u003e\n  \u003c/a\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eI see that I should trigger solver manually and it seems to be quite expensive if I do it sequentially for each character as they could be ran in parallel.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhat would be the best way to implement full body IK rig with minimal changes to Urho3D? What would be an ideal way to do it?\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2021-04-01T08:24:34.733Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":6,"reads":34,"readers_count":33,"score":36.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":6777,"topic_slug":"full-body-ik-rig","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KLjTU0yKS00","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"IK Rig: Procedural Pose Animation - YouTube","clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":604,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":42249,"name":"é­”å¤§å†œ ğğğ³ ç¾æ‹›èœ","username":"Modanung","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/modanung/{size}/3290_2.png","created_at":"2021-04-01T10:30:11.507Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eThat sounds a bit like my blue PiRMIT concept, in terms of rig-agnostic animations. Itâ€™s core idea is setting transform ranges for bones, mapping them to tendons and using normalized values to control these. This should allow for clenching a fist or posing the spine with a handful of characters, as well as sign language. The range and tendon mappings would be in red PiRMIT, which should also be able to define/generate the rig and mesh. Thatâ€™s where my quest for a better curve started, from which Iâ€™m working my way back up. Red PiRMIT will basically function as a \u003ccode\u003eCyberplasm\u003c/code\u003e markup language.\u003cbr\u003e\n\u003cimg src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/hole.png?v=9\" title=\":hole:\" class=\"emoji only-emoji\" alt=\":hole:\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2021-04-01T11:42:33.607Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":33,"readers_count":32,"score":6.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":6777,"topic_slug":"full-body-ik-rig","display_username":"é­”å¤§å†œ ğğğ³ ç¾æ‹›èœ","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":3,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":192,"hidden":false,"trust_level":0,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_suspended":true,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":fals